11:40.296 --> 11:45.483
It must have been difficult having him for a 
subordinate, having Rickover for a subordinate.

11:48.347 --> 11:53.053
I could usually agree with

11:54.974 --> 12:00.602
with the things that were the Commission's 
responsibility in his job. And he was answering,

12:00.622 --> 12:04.688
of course, to the Department of Defense in his 
other hat. And that's where the real problem

12:04.988 --> 12:11.237
was. Because ours was essentially research and 
development on various aspects of the reactor

12:11.938 --> 12:19.429
itself. the procurement of that reactor and its 
installation and the submarine and the submarine

12:19.595 --> 12:28.926
contract and all that was, that was a defense 
problem. And I'm sure I couldn't have gotten along

12:28.946 --> 12:34.112
with him if I'd had all that responsibility. But we 
gave him support in the nuclear side of the thing

12:34.133 --> 12:45.366
and we were able to agree on what the budget should 
be and how he should run it overall. And having done

12:46.477 --> 12:58.527
that and got it through Congress, I could turn it 
over to him, and then all I had to do was audit it

12:46.477 --> 12:58.527
after that, because he ran it okay, no problem. So 
there was not such a tremendous area of

13:00.929 --> 13:10.217
disagreement for us to get at each other's throat 
about. So we got along fine. And I admire Rickover

13:13.420 --> 13:16.062
in a lot of ways. I think he thinks he knows too damn 
much about too many things, and I think it's always

13:16.733 --> 13:27.405
dangerous when a guy gets himself into that frame 
of mind.

13:30.348 --> 13:34.093
He's an authority on education, among other 
things. He's written a couple of books I have in

13:34.133 --> 13:46.707
there on education, what's wrong with American 
education.

13:48.323 --> 14:17.723
Whether I like him or don't like him, or whether I 
like his characteristics or don't like them, or

13:48.323 --> 14:17.723
whether I think he ought to be in the Navy until he's 
82 or retired 20 years ago, I still have to face the

13:48.323 --> 14:17.723
fact that he has been consistent and persistent 
enough that we, the United States, have a damn good

13:48.323 --> 14:17.723
underwater naval capability.

14:18.192 --> 14:19.874
it badly. And without Rick, I'm not sure we'd have 
it. And so, whatever else I might think about it,

14:24.679 --> 14:31.126
I'm thankful that he was there. How did he ever stay 
in the Navy until he was 82?

14:40.416 --> 14:45.662
He stayed there by one mechanism. He convinced the 
the Joint Committee of the Congress, Joint

14:47.875 --> 15:04.289
Committee on Atomic Energy of the Congress, that 
he was right and the Navy was wrong,

14:47.875 --> 15:04.289
and they promoted him the first time. They forced 
the Navy to promote him and kept him on there. He

15:10.895 --> 15:16.600
took advantage of that, and he kept the Congress

15:17.609 --> 15:22.433
fully informed at all times, Congress being the 
joint committee primarily.

15:25.416 --> 15:44.494
And he became very close friends of people who were 
chairmen of the joint committee, Senator

15:25.416 --> 15:44.494
Anderson from New Mexico and Congressman 
Holifield from California, who kind of

15:25.416 --> 15:44.494
alternated the chairmanship.

15:45.115 --> 15:51.821
