I wanted to have just your opinion on the neutron 
bomb.

17:25.843 --> 17:27.605
I mean, whether we should have it or not? Well, yes, 
the neutron bomb is not new. No.

17:38.144 --> 17:42.630
people thought about it even before I was involved 
in the atomic energy business. And that principle

17:42.730 --> 17:49.219
has been under test for quite a long time. And it was 
finally developed so that it, as a practical

17:51.322 --> 18:00.655
weapon, could be used. And its effect has been 
explained.

18:05.178 --> 18:19.681
So it becomes now a question of, is that an effect 
that we need in our arsenal

18:05.178 --> 18:19.681
in the current position we're in in the world 
vis-a-vis the Soviet Union? And I think the answer

18:21.203 --> 18:23.627
to that is clearly yes. I think we ought to make it 
and stockpile it, regardless of what the hell

18:25.149 --> 18:29.937
anybody else thinks. And if a time ever comes that 
we need to use it in our own interest, use it,

18:30.946 --> 18:41.023
whether anybody else likes it or not.

18:45.631 --> 18:56.329
Because Western Europe, Italy,

18:45.631 --> 18:56.329
or I shouldn't cite Italy, any of them over there,

18:59.498 --> 19:07.211
We're going to be hauling louder than anybody else 
if the time comes and we need to use it and we don't

18:59.498 --> 19:07.211
have it. How come you didn't have it? So it's a good 
weapon and it's for a good purpose. It's one we need

19:15.504 --> 19:19.971
in our arsenal and I think we ought to get on with it. 
Okay. Now I want to go back and I want to ask you about

19:20.172 --> 19:25.320
the development of storage sites for atomic 
weapons. At first we didn't have any atomic

19:25.756 --> 19:30.664
weapons and then we started to develop them. What 
were the problems with building storage sites?

19:33.568 --> 19:36.233
How did we pick storage sites?

19:39.798 --> 19:48.372
Well, there were really two major problems 
initially I'm talking about.

19:52.705 --> 20:22.662
One was how did one store these so that

19:52.705 --> 20:22.662
it would be almost impossible for anyone to get 
access to them, either to take them, that is, take

19:52.705 --> 20:22.662
them because we're the only ones in the world who 
had them at that time, take them from a secrecy

19:52.705 --> 20:22.662
standpoint,

20:23.992 --> 20:37.866
And how could you prevent access to them by anyone 
who wanted to use them for some other purpose,

20:23.992 --> 20:37.866
such as terror or blackmail or whatnot?

20:41.727 --> 21:03.701
And how could you protect them from a major 
situation in which there was limited invasion or

20:41.727 --> 21:03.701
insurrection or something in which there was a 
force available to try to take them by force?

21:03.721 --> 21:09.270
And of course, the other thing, the other major 
consideration at the time Under what conditions

21:10.651 --> 21:25.215
do you store them so that if there was an accidental 
detonation, the least amount of damage would be

21:10.651 --> 21:25.215
done? Damage to people, to the surrounding 
country, to the installation itself, to any other

21:27.559 --> 21:37.435
weapon that you would have?

21:41.262 --> 22:05.958
So the answer to all of these, the best answer 
anyone could come up with, turned out to be

21:41.262 --> 22:05.958
cutting back into mountains, into solid rock, 
with chambers to store these under controlled

21:41.262 --> 22:05.958
conditions of humidity, temperature, and this 
sort of thing. Places where they could be secured

22:14.017 --> 22:29.820
individually in

22:14.017 --> 22:29.820
their compartments, in an area that was large 
enough that if something happened to this one, the

22:14.017 --> 22:29.820
one next to it wouldn't be affected, and so on. And 
then to enclose the entire area and guard it in a

22:31.742 --> 22:42.758
manner to deny access to the site, even though 
people presumably when they got on site couldn't

22:43.210 --> 22:52.058
get into the individual storage locations.

22:57.583 --> 23:03.189
So this was, that's the way it was accomplished. 
Now are these sites, are they top secret, or can you

23:03.209 --> 23:07.893
tell me where some of those are? No, I don't know. 
what their classification are now. As a matter of

23:18.035 --> 23:23.064
fact, I don't even know where they are now. So 
they've changed over the years? That's good. Oh,

23:26.971 --> 23:29.235
yeah. Why do they change them? I mean, if they have a 
successful site or one that's secure. Well, they

23:33.622 --> 23:34.865
haven't changed them all. I don't mean that. 
They've produced a lot of weapons since I got out of

23:38.392 --> 23:43.019
the business, so I don't know where they have put 
them. And that's good, I don't want them. But they

23:46.724 --> 24:01.587
are located usually within a few miles of 
locations from which they're going to be used. Oh,

24:02.548 --> 24:03.910
I see. from the major missile launch areas, from 
the major sack areas, from the major attack areas.

24:17.516 --> 24:19.158
So there are a number of sites. I built five while I 
was in Nashua because it was our job to find them,

24:19.439 --> 24:33.559
build them, occupy them, take custody of weapons 
and put them in them and see that they stay there.

24:34.720 --> 24:37.183
see that they were maintained and ready to go.

24:40.347 --> 24:42.129
So I built five of the five. The one everyone knows 
about, I suspect, is near Albuquerque, the first

24:42.149 --> 24:48.776
one. It's

24:49.137 --> 24:55.224
still there, and I'm sure it's still occupied. 
Now, why did you leave the Armed Forces Special

24:57.006 --> 25:03.073
Weapons Project? Was your tour of duty on? Yes, it 
was. See I had been in there

25:08.451 --> 25:17.068
nearly six years, about that. And I had been the 
deputy and then I became the chief and it was time to

25:17.088 --> 25:26.867
do something else.

25:29.311 --> 25:35.499
Well, were you happy with your next assignment as 
the commander, Joint Task Force 7, Nuclear Test

25:29.311 --> 25:35.499
Organization? Yes, very. Very. Yeah, it was a very 
good assignment, a very, very rough problem. One

25:46.874 --> 25:50.559
that would be extremely difficult to handle. Now, 
why were you only there a year? because that's how

25:53.020 --> 25:56.845
long it took to do it. We finished the job. Okay. 
Let's talk about that. What were your

26:01.912 --> 26:03.394
responsibilities?

26:06.438 --> 26:19.095
The

26:06.438 --> 26:19.095
Joint Task Force, in this case Joint Task Force 
Seven,

26:06.438 --> 26:19.095
has the job of testing

26:21.843 --> 26:36.022
overseas, it doesn't operate within the United 
States, such weapons and devices as the Atomic

26:21.843 --> 26:36.022
Energy Commission and the Secretary of Defense 
might direct.

26:39.347 --> 26:46.416
This one was primarily a development test program 
to be conducted and

26:47.206 --> 27:06.496
primarily in Inuitak, although also included 
Bikini and Kwajalein, and as it turned out,

26:47.206 --> 27:06.496
Johnson Island, before we got through.

27:06.516 --> 27:12.606
The emphasis of the testing was on medium- and 
high-yield thermonuclear devices to determine

27:14.459 --> 27:42.711
their characteristics and decide which ones 
would go into production for what purposes and in

27:14.459 --> 27:42.711
what configurations, as well as to get a number of 
weapons effects, many of the weapons effects. two

27:43.990 --> 27:57.937
of the detonations were to be conducted at high 
altitude,

27:43.990 --> 27:57.937
primarily for effects purposes, although we were 
also testing the devices.

28:02.786 --> 28:03.788
And they worked. I've forgotten how many tests 
were conducted in that series, but it was like 38 or

28:05.523 --> 28:12.750
40.

28:22.500 --> 28:26.845
What were the major—what did you learn from these 
tests? The major? What did you learn from these

28:27.766 --> 28:31.750
tests and the new information?

28:42.766 --> 29:03.273
From the standpoint of development of the 
weapons,

28:42.766 --> 29:03.273
it is so highly technical and is a

28:42.766 --> 29:03.273
space and time there that I would have to go back and 
refresh myself

28:42.766 --> 29:03.273
to be specific about. But we moved to stockpile 
after those tests. with several warheads that

29:09.749 --> 29:27.775
were firmed up as a result of those taps, so that we 
knew exactly what their configuration was,

29:09.749 --> 29:27.775
exactly what their yield was, and exactly what 
their effects were, so that we could then put them

29:28.480 --> 29:35.149
into a weapons system, establish those weapons 
characteristics, and go to production. That was,

29:36.090 --> 29:44.060
of course, the real big achievement of the test 
series.

29:44.081 --> 29:53.593
We had many weapons effects programs that either 
confirmed or developed a

29:54.721 --> 29:59.006
information we needed to further our weapons 
effects business. And the one at high altitude

30:01.069 --> 30:15.868
gave us the effects on the ionosphere and on the 
atmosphere and

30:01.069 --> 30:15.868
answered many technical questions.

30:18.751 --> 30:25.439
I think eliminated the need for further testing up 
there and certainly took away any doubts about

30:18.751 --> 30:25.439
what it did. One

30:27.401 --> 30:46.142
thing I wanted to ask was what weapon systems, new 
weapon systems resulted from your test at Joint

30:46.831 --> 30:53.360
Task Force

30:46.831 --> 30:53.360
7. Can you talk about that? I think that there 
probably were none that you could say this

30:55.883 --> 31:03.273
resulted directly from this test. Weapons 
systems take many years and many considerations

31:03.433 --> 31:11.284
and probably usually many tests. And so while this 
one

31:17.695 --> 31:23.403
conform many aspects or develop many new planning 
factors and things like that. As far as I can

31:23.443 --> 31:31.775
remember right now, it didn't develop a 
particular weapon system. It

31:31.855 --> 31:40.648
cannot come as a result of one test.

31:42.940 --> 31:53.610
It gave us the information we needed to make the 
decisions as to what warheads to put on several

31:42.940 --> 31:53.610
weapons and weapons systems.

31:59.915 --> 32:03.599
But of course it's only one element of such a 
decision.

32:06.321 --> 32:07.262
Why did you retire? From the Air Force? Yes. Well, I 
was asked to take this job as general manager of AEC

32:12.083 --> 32:30.122
by people that I had a great deal of respect for. Mr. 
Strauss, who was chairman of the AEC at that time,

32:30.142 --> 32:39.492
Louis Strauss, and John McCone, who was coming in 
to be chairman shortly, and by President

32:40.012 --> 32:48.743
Eisenhower, who was president at the time. And it 
was a, to me, a real challenge in terms of my earlier

32:50.405 --> 33:00.838
decisions and earlier experience. And I wanted to 
know whether I could do something outside of the

33:03.164 --> 33:10.775
military because I hadn't had really an 
opportunity to find out.

33:14.421 --> 33:22.172
So I debated it hard and

33:14.421 --> 33:22.172
finally decided to do it. Whether it was a good 
thing to do, I haven't any idea because I went to see

33:28.308 --> 33:35.922
General White, who was Chief of Staff of the Air 
Force at that time, to see if he would honor my

33:28.308 --> 33:35.922
request for early retirement.

